{"cursor":"40965","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In social psychology, 'group polarization' refers to the tendency for groups to\nmake decisions that are more extreme than the initial inclination of its\nmembers. These more extreme decisions are towards greater risk if individuals'\ninitial tendencies are to be risky and towards greater caution if individuals'\ninitial tendencies are to be cautious. The phenomenon also holds that\na group's attitude toward a situation may change in the sense that the\nindividuals' initial attitudes have strengthened and intensified after group\ndiscussion.\n","linknr":309,"url":"Group_polarization","recorded":1362477175,"links":23,"instances":["psychology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Group processes","Human behavior","Motivation"],"headings":["Overview","History and origins","Major theoretical approaches","Major empirical findings","Choice shifts","Real-life applications","Controversy","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Psi2.svg/28px-Psi2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Logo_sociology.svg/28px-Logo_sociology.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["attitude","psychology"]],"members":["attitude"],"related":["Social_psychology","Attitude_(psychology)","Group_behavior","Public_policy","Terrorism","Political_party","Jury","Punitive_damages","Civil_trial","Social_media","Facebook","Twitter","Social_proof","Social_comparison_theory","Daniel_Isenberg","Self-categorization_theory","Social_identity_theory","Self-categorization_theory","Ingroup","Prejudice","Holocaust","Adversarial_process","Attitude_polarization","Confirmation_bias","Deindividuation","Group-serving_bias","Groupthink","Id